ve to pry it from our cold, dead, fingers. That product, of course, is Micr=
osoft Excel.=C2=A0
Anyone who has worked in finance or consulting grew up on it, learned to lo=
ve it over thousands of hours of practice and improvement. Whether they rea=
lized it or not, they were becoming programmers, or at least no-code practi=
tioners before the no-code movement took off. =E2=80=9CProficient in the Mi=
crosoft Office Suite=E2=80=9D is so meaningless that it=E2=80=99s become a =
meme, but the ability to bend one specific Office program, Excel, to one=E2=
=80=99s will is a badge of honor.=C2=A0
But the enduring, passionate user fervor for the product isn=E2=80=99t even=
 its most unique attribute. Excel=E2=80=99s most lasting impact extends bey=
ond the spreadsheet itself.
Excel may be the most influential software ever built. It is a canonical ex=
ample of Steve Job=E2=80=99s bicycle of the mind [https://email.mg2.substac=
k.com/c/eJxFkM1uhDAMhJ-GHFH-CYccWlV7as89opAYNlpIUEgW8fbNLodKli15ZI_msybDHNO=
